At the opening session of the 42nd General Assembly Monday, Third
World countries led by Brazil blamed industrialized nations in part
for perpetuating their poverty.

Foreign Minister Roberto de Abreau Sodre of Brazil said that the Third
World economic picture was dimming "due to the lack of progress in
international economic relations."

A similar theme sounded Monday in West Berlin, where finance ministers
of 22 developed or developing countries demanded "more forceful
action" to help Third World countries repay $1.2 trillion in
debts. Foreign Affairs Secretary Obed Asamoah of Ghana asked creditors
to write off some debts.  Ghana has an estimated foreign debt of $2.8
billion.</SUM>

