SUMMARIZER="D">   

John Hatch, founder of the non-profit Foundation for International
Community Assistance that promotes village banking to encourage
enterprise in the Third World, developed a concept of using small
revolving loans to poor women to finance their private enterprise,
allowing them to create savings while paying interest and qualifying
for bigger loans.

The series of loans, starting at $50, is renewable over three years to
a ceiling of $300, allowing recipients to reach a level at which they
can qualify for commercial credit.

What Hatch envisioned five years ago has translated into 400 village
banks in nine countries.  Portfolios total $1.6 million, with a 96
percent repayment rate.</SUM>

