When Lewis Preston takes over as president of the World Bank this
September, he will have to find a way to best promote development in
the Third World.

The bank has not had an effective president since the 1980s when
Robert McNamara headed the institution.

Grinding poverty is a near universal condition in much of the world
where 1 billion people live on less than one dollar a day.

In the past decade Third World countries have gone backwards.  Real
per capita incomes have declined substantially in sub-Saharan Africa
and the Middle East, and mildly in Latin America.</SUM>

<SUM
